BELFAST, Maine — When Mike Hurley became mayor of Belfast 25 years ago, he didn’t expect it would lead him to a new business.

“I’m a serial entrepreneur,” Hurley said of himself. “I've always been self-employed.”

He became mayor the year after finding an inspiration, halfway across the country in Chicago, called Cows on Parade. The Windy City placed several hundred large fiberglass cows on downtown streets and found artists to decorate them.

The cows were a big hit in that city, Hurley explained, and gave him an idea: “We’ve got to do this in Belfast. That’s what I thought,” Hurley said.

In the summer of 2000, the Maine city held its first Belfast Bearfest, with 40-some fiberglass bears, decorated by artists, spread around the historic downtown. As with the Chicago cows, he says the bears were a hit with most locals and crowds of visitors.

“It was phenomenal,” Hurley recalled of the public’s response. “Nothing works like this. To see kids run from one bear to the next with family in tow.”

The public response to Bearfest led to an unexpected result.

“And immediately the phone is ringing. ‘We want to do a duck fest, a golf ball fest, a moose fest, dinosaurs.’ And I very quickly go, 'I can help you with that.'"

Thus was born Fiberglass Farm, a new business for Hurley that’s still making animals, and many other things, more than two decades later.

Hurley says, initially, they provided cows, bears, moose, and other fiberglass animals to towns that wanted to do something similar to BearFest. Then the calls came for one-of-a-kind objects to display around the country.

“We made, like, the largest longhorn steer for the University of Texas. We made a life-size T- Rex. I’ve visited that in Orlando… We made a car for people. We made cooling towers for a nuclear power plant information center.”

In Maine, Fiberglass Farm created Babe the Blue Ox for Rumford, and a 17-foot Loon that sits beside the lake in downtown Lincoln.

More recently, they provided giant sturgeon—modeled after the fish that spend summers in the Kennebec River—that were decorated by artists around downtown Augusta.

Most of those creations were not made in Maine. Hurley says he worked with fiberglass businesses in several other states that are better able to produce multiple objects or meet the timetables for the projects. He does use one artist in Maine, mostly for individual projects.

And in the last dozen years, a growing part of the farm’s business has been about pro sports. Starting with bobbleheads—and not the little hand-held ones that get given out at ballparks or sold in the gift shop.

“Eight-foot-tall bobbleheads,” he explained. Made to resemble popular players on various teams, the sculptures are displayed for fans at stadiums and other sports venues.

Like the Belfast bears and Chicago cows, the giant bobbleheads got attention.

“And then you get another call like, 'Hey, I’m calling from the Green Bay Packers,' or 'I’m calling from San Francisco Giants.'"

Word spread and business grew.

Then came the request for a giant version of a team’s championship ring. That business also took off.

