"We’re making two things for the Dodgers. They wanted a Fernando Valenzuela bobblehead, so we’re in the middle of making that, and now, because they won the World Series last year, they want a championship ring, so we’re working on that."

The ring duplicates the ones the players received, and is four feet tall or more, providing fans with a great photo-op.

It's become a good business for Fiberglass Farm, but Hurley would like to get more.

“Last year I made a championship ring for the Dodgers, baseball World Series, they won it. Florida Panthers won the National Hockey League and the Philadelphia Eagles won the Super Bowl. I want to know what’s wrong with the NBA? They haven’t bought a ring yet!”

And closer to home, there’s one particular team he wants to hear from.

“And by the way,” he saID, only half joking, “why haven’t the Patriots bought a ring? That’s who I would love to do.”

Hurley admits he’s never been that big a sports fan, but he clearly enjoys the sports business. The response from fans, after all, may not be that different from the excitement kids showed for the bears, 25 years ago. And that response, he’s learned, is what makes the displays good for communities, be they sports fans or local downtowns.

“If I didn’t have the grasp of what it meant for the community, of the power of this fiberglass meets art meets downtowns, I would have walked right by it. Bears, cows, whatever,” Hurley said. 

Seeing the power of those cows, and then the bears, started him on a fiberglass journey from Belfast that hasn’t stopped.

